Steps taken:

Once we learned the infrastructure was already there, it was just learning how to make Alert Rules on Grafana. 

Watching tutorials and trying them at the same time helped a lot. We made a server on Discord so that way we could test it out before I was given my account 
from Prof Bisesti. On my intitial attempts we made a few errors of trying to watch and do at the same time. Once we read and watched the material we were able to
understand what we were going to have to do to make these alert rules be a success. 

First I had to set up a High CPU Alert Rule which consisted of: 
  - On the left sidebar under 'Alerting'
  - Click 'Alert Rules'
  - CLick 'New Alert Rule'
  - Name the Rule as 'High CPU Usage'
  - Select the folder to save it in which was 'Alerts' in the Dashboard
  - Set the 'Evaluation Group' to 'Rack Server'

Next Step was to Add the Code to the Query:
  - The Query code is: 100 - (avg by(instance)(rate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100)
  - node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"} is a counter metric from Node Exporter that measures the total number of seonds the CPU has spent in a given mode.
    -{mode="idle"} filters the metric to only include idle CPU time
  - This part selects total accumulated seconds where CPU was idle

  - rate(...[5m]) calculates the per-second average increase over the last 5 minutes, since it is a counter it converts into the fraction of time
  the CPU was idle per second over a 5 minute period.

  - avg by(instance)(...)
    - Each CPU core reports separately
  - This part:
    - Averages the idle rate  
    - Groups the result by instance
    - Combines all CPU cores into a single value per machine
  - This gives you the average idle percentage per instance

  - *100 converts from decimal/fraction to percentage .72 -> 72
      - Idle = 72%
  - 100 - (...) flips idle into usage  
      - CPU Usage = 100-72 = 28%

Next Step is to set your Alert Conditions

  - You will see Expression -> Threshold
  - Warning Condition set to:
    - Name of Condition: High CPU Usage
    - WHEN: A (Rule Name)
    - IS ABOVE: (Your desired percentage)
    - FOR: (Designated time interval) 
  - Add another Threshold 
    - Name of Condition: Critical Condition
    - WHEN: A (Rule Name)
    - IS ABOVE: (Your desired percentage)
    - FOR: (Designated time interval)
Grafana will automatically evaluate the highest severity first

To reduce the chance of getting spammed with Alerts when over the threshold:
  -Set Reduce and Evaluate Settings
    -Reduce: Last
    -Evaluate Every: 1m
    -For: 5m

For Discord it is good to Add Labels, so under the Labels add:
  - severity=warning
  - severity=critical

You can add custom anotations as well to come up when the alert fires. 



Next step is to set the High RAM Usage Alert, very simiar to the High CPU Usage Alert.

Set your New Alert Rule:
  - Name: High RAM Usage
  - Folder: Alerts
  - Evaluation Group: Rack Server

Next is to add your code to the query, this is a little different than the High CPU Usage rule as it is 
using different datasets. 

  - Query Code: 100 * (1 - (node_memory_MemAvailable_bytes{job="node'} / node_memory_MemTotal_bytes{job="node}))

This code takes the memory available and divides it by the total memory which gives a fraction of RAM still available. 
Then subtract it from 1 to get the fraction of used RAM. 
Then multiply it by 100 to convert it to the percentage of RAM used. 

For this you want to make sure you use MemAvailable, not MemFree because:

  Linux uses RAM for:
    - cache
    - buffers
    - filesystem cache
  These are reclaimable, so the MemAvailable option will give you a more accurate "real usage" value

Then you can set your desired thresholds:
  - Warning Condition: 
    - Warning: > (percentage) for (time interval)
    - Critical: > (percentage) for (time interval)

I set the same evaluation settings as the High CPU Usage and same severity labels. 



Lastly is to set up the Alerts for the / main filesystem. 

Set your new Alert Rule:
  - Name: Disk Usage NVMe Root
  - Folder: Alerts
  - Evaluation Group: Rack Server

Code for Query is: 100 - (node_filesystem_avail_bytes{mountpoint="/",fstype!~"tmpfs|overlay"} / node_filesystem_size_bytes{mountpoint="/",fstype!~"tmpfs|overlay"}))

This code has the same idea as the High RAM Usage Code; divides the available space by the total space then converts it into a percentage. 

Then you can set your thresholds:
  - Warning: > (percentage) for (time interval)
  - Critical: > (percentage) for (time interval)
Set your severity labels if you desire and annotations

The second NVME Alert Rule is almost identical, one thing we are changing is in our code which is the mountpoint,
instead of {mountpoint="/",fstype...} it is {mountpoint="/data",fstype...}

This will monitor the usage of the /data disk while the first NVMe Alert Rule calculates the root disk. 

If all went well with your query and thresholds, your alerts should be successfully set up and ready to party. 




  
    
